I'm Brady Enstad,
and I've primarily

00:00:40.389 --> 00:00:41.930
been the interviewer
for the project.

00:00:44.730 --> 00:00:48.110
LEXI DIEN: I'm Lexi Dien, and
I've primarily the videographer

00:00:48.110 --> 00:00:50.875
and video editor.

00:00:50.875 --> 00:00:52.000
YI ZHONG: And I'm Yi Zhong.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.061
I've been the lead
scribe for this project.

00:00:55.061 --> 00:00:55.561
[INAUDIBLE]

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:01.170
So the first thing
we started with

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:03.755
is contextual inquiry using
the HAAT model so just

00:01:03.755 --> 00:01:05.900
a quick review of what
the HAAT model is.

00:01:05.900 --> 00:01:08.480
We are looking at the
human activity assistive

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:11.360
technology and then the
context, and then trying

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:13.090
to get all the
aspect of the problem

00:01:13.090 --> 00:01:14.897
that we're trying to solve.

00:01:14.897 --> 00:01:16.730
So the first thing we're
going to talk about

00:01:16.730 --> 00:01:18.930
is Paul, our client.

00:01:18.930 --> 00:01:22.410
He has been an amputee
for the past 30 years.

00:01:22.410 --> 00:01:25.230
He worked in IT before, but
for the past two or three years

00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:27.660
he had a really
severe hip problem.

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:30.420
He couldn't really get around,
and he had to stay home a lot.

00:01:30.420 --> 00:01:32.940
And he had a surgery
in June, so he's

00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:35.274
able to walk again but
with reduced arm strength.

00:01:35.274 --> 00:01:37.690
So that means he wouldn't be
able to walk a long distance.

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:41.370
He wouldn't be able to
carry really heavy things.

00:01:41.370 --> 00:01:43.420
And this is the AT he uses.

00:01:43.420 --> 00:01:46.500
It's custom-made
forearm crutches.

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:50.160
It's really expensive, and
it's customized to Paul.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.370
And so some of the
activities that he

00:01:52.370 --> 00:01:56.060
wanted us to do a project on
are self-standing crutches,

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:58.230
a mechanism to pull
a suitcase, something

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:00.280
to carry a slice
of pizza, something

00:02:00.280 --> 00:02:03.380
to carry a cup of coffee,
a self-standing umbrella,

00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:05.490
so he doesn't get
wet in the rain.

00:02:05.490 --> 00:02:07.360
So all of these activities
just kind of show

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:09.897
that Paul really just wants
to do things that people do

00:02:09.897 --> 00:02:12.480
and that he really wants to get
out there again after this hip

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:14.410
problem isn't bothering him.

00:02:14.410 --> 00:02:18.090
And we narrowed it
down to this problem;

00:02:18.090 --> 00:02:20.860
this is a quote by
Paul, "it would be nice

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:23.330
if I can bring my way
of a cup of coffee.

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:24.360
Wouldn't that be nice?"

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:26.235
And we think, yeah, so
this is the problem we

00:02:26.235 --> 00:02:27.570
that ended up pursuing.

00:02:27.570 --> 00:02:31.792
And then we dove into the
context of this problem more.

00:02:31.792 --> 00:02:33.500
So looking at it from
a few perspectives,

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:35.570
so culturally he doesn't
want to use a wheelchair.

00:02:35.570 --> 00:02:37.278
Like I said, he had
a hip problem before,

00:02:37.278 --> 00:02:39.220
so he had to be on
an electric scooter,

00:02:39.220 --> 00:02:41.030
and he actually
didn't like that all.

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:41.675
He wants to use crutches.

00:02:41.675 --> 00:02:42.930
He wants to be able to stand.

00:02:42.930 --> 00:02:45.590
But because of the
nature of his injury,

00:02:45.590 --> 00:02:48.480
he couldn't use prosthetics,
so he had to use crutches.

00:02:48.480 --> 00:02:50.761
And socially his wife helps
him with many activities,

00:02:50.761 --> 00:02:52.010
including bringing him coffee.

00:02:52.010 --> 00:02:54.610
But his wife does have
work, so he needs to do this

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:56.580
by himself when he's at home.

00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:59.210
And physically he just wants
to do this in his apartment.

00:02:59.210 --> 00:03:01.085
When he brews a cup of
coffee in the morning.

00:03:01.085 --> 00:03:03.780
He wants to be able to
carry it to the living room,

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:05.113
something like simple like that.

00:03:10.110 --> 00:03:12.340
And looking at it one
statement, so this

00:03:12.340 --> 00:03:15.190
is our problem
statement-- a design,

00:03:15.190 --> 00:03:19.770
a mechanism, that help him carry
a cup of coffee around his home

00:03:19.770 --> 00:03:21.690
without spilling,
and such that he

00:03:21.690 --> 00:03:23.130
doesn't have to grab onto it.

00:03:23.130 --> 00:03:25.100
And this is the way he
carries it right now.

00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:27.032
It's kind of a grip
and then while trying

00:03:27.032 --> 00:03:29.240
to use crutches at the same
time, so you can imagine,

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:30.530
it's really tough.

00:03:30.530 --> 00:03:32.870
And we kind of break it down
to two main problems, which

00:03:32.870 --> 00:03:35.562
is how do we do it hands-free,
so he doesn't have to hold it,

00:03:35.562 --> 00:03:37.770
and how do we do no-spill,
so he doesn't spill coffee

00:03:37.770 --> 00:03:39.320
on his hands.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:44.380
And I'll let Lexi talk
about the success metrics.

00:03:44.380 --> 00:03:47.620
LEXI DIEN: So right
now, basically, Paul

00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:51.430
can carry a cup of coffee
around with that claw grip,

00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:53.080
and he can only fill
it about a third

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:55.450
full if he doesn't want to
spill it all over his hands

00:03:55.450 --> 00:03:57.260
or on the floor.

00:03:57.260 --> 00:04:02.210
We'd like to make that a
larger amount of coffee,

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:05.600
and we'd like to make sure
that it isn't spilled.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:09.896
So for a livable goal we
decided that maybe the coffee

00:04:09.896 --> 00:04:13.940
would be 2/3 full and
he could not spill it.

00:04:13.940 --> 00:04:15.610
And then as an
ambitious goal, we

00:04:15.610 --> 00:04:19.930
would say 3/4 full
and also no spill.

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:21.779
Some other additional
things we talked about

00:04:21.779 --> 00:04:24.550
were making it easy to
remove from his crutch

00:04:24.550 --> 00:04:28.795
or from whatever it is;
the technology is just

00:04:28.795 --> 00:04:32.500
easy to use and take away.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:36.190
And so we said 20 seconds for
a livable and then 10 seconds

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:36.820
preferably.

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:40.360
We want it to be
as quick possible.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:42.080
We also decided that
we wanted to take

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:44.180
Paul's perspective into this.

00:04:44.180 --> 00:04:46.060
I think that's very important.

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:47.860
We wanted, especially,
him to rate

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:52.420
it, and we're hoping ambitiously
to get an 8 out of 10.

00:04:52.420 --> 00:04:55.260
More livably, we
think a 6 out of 10

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:57.240
will be something
that we'd accept,

00:04:57.240 --> 00:05:01.360
but we really want to get as
high as possible on his rating.

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:06.060
And the last thing we
wanted to make sure

00:05:06.060 --> 00:05:10.400
is that we actually are
able to use it with a mug.

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:15.060
He uses his own mugs, and wants
to be able to use his own mugs.

00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:18.710
So we want to make sure that
it works for at least that mug,

00:05:18.710 --> 00:05:22.870
and preferably it works
for a lot of his mugs

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:26.190
or all of his mugs.

00:05:26.190 --> 00:05:30.600
So we're going to show you
the video that we put together

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:33.271
that gives you a little bit
more background into Paul.

